{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_noone_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600702/1930050101/0059.xml":{"full_text":"A-10\n61410 TAKE PART\nIN FETE SATURDAY\nChildren\u2019s Festival to Be\nHeld in Afternoon at\nCentral Center.\nThe fifth annual children's festival\nof the Community Center Department\nwill be held Saturday afternoon at 2\no\u2019clock at Central Community Center,\nThirteenth and Clifton streets, with 614\nparticipants from the It centers\nthroughout the city.\nVari-colored balloons will be used to\ndecorate the stage, and following the\nperformance will be given to the chil\ndren.\nGroups of children from Southeast\nCenter will take part in four numbers,\nfeaturing an original dance plan en\ntitled \u2018\u2018The Princess Outwits Her Prime\nMinister,\" written and directed by Miss\nEvelyn Davis, and an original shadow\ngraph entitled \u201cThe Witch and the\nProg,\" directed by Mrs. Donna Taggart,\nfor which special settings and lighting\nhave been arranged by Harold Snyder.\nMembers of the Cast.\nThe cast for \u201cThe Princess Outwits\nHer Prime Minister\u201d includes: Marian\nRuehl, Ella Bergling, Florence Close,\nPrecosia Crosby, Prances Gallagher,\nAlice Garrison, Rosaline Hepner, Gladys\nHendricks, Evelyn McLaren, Mary I\nPrances Partridge, Evelyn Simpson,\nShirley Schafer, Mary Traynor, Bar-\nbara Weiss, Florence Cady, Margaret\nColin, Mary Colin, Jacqueline Embrey, I\nElsie Smithson, Sylvia Berlin, Vivian\nHendrix, Dorothy Simpson, Margaret\nSchwenk, Beatrice Bishop, Rosaline\nBishop, Lorraine Fisher, Ardith Harris,\nElaine Harris, Ruth Kravitz, Dorothy\nNolan, Katherine Clark, Marjorie Gris\naan, Ruth Harris, Wilhelmina Schmidt\nEdna Simonds, Elolse Snipes, Ruth\nHullings and Margaret Hell.\nThose taking part in the shadow\ngraph, \u201cThe Witch and the Prog,\u201d are:\nKathryn Phillips, Ruth Rappaport,\nJames Cochrane, Virginia MacCauley,\nEdward Schenk, Dorothy Agnes Smith,\nDorothy Ellen Smith, Betty Titlow,\nMargaret Powell, Maude Halterman,\nYvonne Tee, Thelma Daniels. Mildred\nPones, Sarah Grits, Prances Wassman,\nKatherine Wassman and Ruby Halfcer\nman.\nIn The Clowns and Monkeys,\u201d also\npresented by Southeast Center, Miss\nSarah Bergling has assisted In the di\nrection, with the following children\ntaking parti Ethel Andre, Barbara\nBuker, Anna Burgess, Lorriane Cloud,\nCatherine Darmstead, Sadie Pox, Alina\nPuller, Thelma Fairall, Natalie Gam\nmon, Irene Green, Ruth Jenkins, Pran\nces Leyer, Adelta Lint, Frances Mc-\nGilllcuddy, Helen Martz, Josephine\nPhipps, Sarah Rosendorf, Mary Ryan,\nClara Smollow, Eleanor Sullivan, Edna\nSweeney, Eleanor Thomas, Mary Bates,\nEvelyn Bates, Minetta Barnes, Betty\nCochrane, Shirley Danov, Dorothy\nDriver, Olive Driver, Pauline Puller,\nMargaret Hall, Eleanora Kravitz, Tal\nmah McConchie, Gladys Marshall,\nMabel Marine, June Protheroe, Lorraine\nShallcross, Jean Strohecker, Betty\nTaylor and Doris Warner.\nDance Number Scheduled.\nThe Prep Dancers of the Southeast\nCenter will offer a dance number, with\nthe following boys and girls taking\npart: Edward Bishop, Beatrice Bishop,\nElla Bergling, Irma Barry, Bobby Barry,\nPeggy Barry, Arthur Branscombe, Mar\ngery Branscombe, George Conger, Mar\ngaret Cox, Katherine Clark, Billie\nCrawford, Precosia Crosby, Harold\nDavis, Dorothy Dix, Virginia Edge,\nJacqueline Embrey, Melvin Fletcher,\nAlice Garrison, Ruth Harris, Margaret\nHell. Rosaline Hepner, Eleanor Hager\nman, Bill Hullings, Ruth Hullings,\nGeorgia Harkness, Vivian Hendrix,\nMary Johnson, Mildred Lewis, Barbara\nMcCarthy, Frances McCormick, Doro\nthy Knowlton, Lorriance Price, Kather\nine Phillips, June Protheroe, Eloise\nSnipes, Marion Ruehl, Shirley Shafer,\nLorraine Schafer, Leslie Schafer, Wil\nbur Schafer, Oeraldlne Tull, Paul Wel\nler, Barbara Weiss, Kay Waite, Helen\nYoung.\nOther groups to appear in the pro\ngram represent the Takoma Park and\nthe Thomson Centers.\nA small admission fee will be asked\nat the door to defray the expense of\nthe festival, as In former years.\nANACOSTIA BRIDGE\nURGED BY CITIZENS\nImprovement of Massachusetts\nAvenue Southeast Is Sought by\nHandle Highlands Oroup.\nImprovement of Massachusetts ave\nnue southeast, including construction\nof a bridge across the Anacostia River\nbetween the present Benning and Penn\nsylvania avenue bridges, was urged in\na resolution adopted last night at a\nmeeting of the Randle Highlands Cit\nizens\u2019 Association in the Orr School.\nThe association also went on lecord\nas favoring the location of a contem\nplated national stadium in the southeast\nsection of the city, near the Pennsyl\nvania Avenue Bridge.\nActing on a resolution formerly\nadopted by the body, the association\ncalled upon the Federation of Citizens\u2019\nAssociations to aid it in bringing about\nthe erection of a statue of MaJ. L\u2019En\nfant, French architect, who drew up\nthe plans for the City of Washington,\nIn the square of that name in South\neast Washington.\nThe association also asked the aid\nof the federation in bringing about\nstreet impro/ements in its territory.\nMusical numbers by Miss Dora Her\nbert. 10-year-old ukelele soloist, fea\ntured the program.\nMilton Collins, president of the asso\nciation, presided at the meeting.\nBREACH OF CONTRACT\nCHARGED TO SHELL CO.\nDefendants in SIOO,OOO Damage\nSuit Deny Blocking Comple-\nAlleging that It was the Shell Co.\nwhich violated the contract for the leas\ning of a number of gas filling stations,\nthe Penn Oil Co., the Penn Realty Co.,\nPaul Hlmmelfarb and Annie Himmel\nfarb today filed answer in the District\nSupreme Court to the suit for SIOO,OOO\ndamages recently brought against them\nby the Shell Oil Co. Through Attorneys\nAlvin L. Newmyer and Joseph L. Tep\nper, the defendants deny that they pre\nvented the completion of the contract\nas charged by the Shell Co., and as\nsert that the Shell Co. sought to impose\n/new terms and conditions on the closing\ndate contrary to the agreement.\nThe defendants ask the dismissal cf\nthe Shell Co. suit, and that they be\ngiven a judgment against the Shell Co.\nfor the SIOO,OOO mentioned in the con\ntract as liquidated damages for a\nbreach.\nFIRE DAMAGES SCHOOL\nDlaze Breaks Out in McMahon Hall\nat Catholic University.\nFire of undetermined origin flaring\ntip in the storeroom of McMahon Hau\nat Catholic University, destroyed ap\nproximately S2OO worth of stationery\nand other school supplies shortly be\nfore 4 o\u2019clock this morning.\nA night watchman making his rounds\nof the building discovered the blaze\nand turned in a fire alarm. The flames\nwere quickly extinguished by firemen\nbefore the blaze could spread to the\nclass rooms located in the same build\ning.\nCHILDREN REHEARSING FOR COMMUNITY FESTIVAL\nJ\nTwo croups from the Thomeon School who will take port in the Children\u2019, Festival, Patorder at Central tilth school,\nStar staff Photo.\nGLENN FORECASTS\nBUSINESS REVIVAL\nIllinois Senator Says Tariff\nBill\u2019s Passage Will Re\nact Well.\nSenator Otis F. Glenn of Illinois pre\ndicted an immediate and extraordinary\nrevival in business all over the United\nStates within 30 days at a breakfast of\nthe Illinois Manufacturers\u2019 Association\nat the Mayflower Hotel this morning.\nThe breakfast was attended by 80\nguests including 25 representatives of\nthe leading Industries of Illionis, mem\nbers of the Illionis congressional dele\ngation and other notables invited by the\nassociation.\nSenator Glenn said an immediate and\nextraordinary revival in business will\ntake place In this country within 30\ndays, with the passage of the tariff\nbill.\n\"It will relieve uncertainty,\u201d he said.\n\"Business will be tremendously ac\ncelerated. Some think there will be no\nbill passed, but I am confident the\nHouse will expedite matters, because\nthere will be little or no controversy\nover rates. The chief debate will be\non the flexible provisions of the tariff,\ngiving the President authority to meet\nchanging competitive conditions, and\nalso on the debenture clause. I predict\nthat the debenture provision will be\ntaken from the bill, and the flexible\nSro vision, as passed by the Senate, will\ne finally adopted with some modifier\ntion.\u201d\nRobert Lamont, who used to be a\nvice president of the association, said\nthat when he first came to Washington\nas Secretary of Commerce he thought\nthat the Department of Commerce only\nwas requested for information and\nservice by small business and industrial\nconcerns, but he said that he got re\nquests from all parts of the country\nfrom all classes of business and for\nservice amounting to 70,000 inquiries\na week. He mentioned specifically oil,\ncotton and copper.\nOPTIMIST CHIEFS FETED\nDistrict Governor and Assistant\nGuests of Local Club.\nHerbert B. Nevius, newly elected gov\nernor of the Sixteenth District, Optimist\nInternational, and Adrian Waring, lieu\ntenant governor, both members of the\nWashington Optimist Club, were the\nguests of honor of the Optimists at the\nclub\u2019s weekly luncheon meeting yes\nterday afternoon at the Hamilton Hotel.\nNevius, in a short talk, outlined plans\nfor expansion of the Optimist Club in\nthe district which now includes Wash\nington and Baltimore. Formation of\nclubs in other cities will be sought, he\nstated, with the Washington and Bal\ntimore club members making \u201cmission\nary\u201d trips to cities in the Virginia and\nMaryland sections nearby.\nOld fashioned\nPie Crust\neasily made\nI Grandmother had a \u2019tune\nI deriul r,c l \u00df* S \u2019tooX to Prepare!\nthey usually took with\nFlako flavor, but\nI that \u2018in lour minutes\nmakes them inCloned recipe\nIt s an old ras\"\u2018 tor conven\nput In a P%Fr*A ln the best\nlent use. Contain* d g\nquality cur :.it You simply K\nshortening. bake \u2014it a\nadd wster, Ji,v o makes crisp.\nso easyt Flak m d dry\nlight, liaky P\u00abL.f the uniiorm\nundercruats. and the gulu\nI sis I\n1 S\u2019/\u00ae r\u00b0\u201d\u2019 I\n-rocer for it.\nA Wmm 15c a package\nTHE EVENING STAR. WASHINGTON, D, C., THURSDAY. MAY 1, 1930.\nPIGEON STEALS NEST FROM ROBIN\nABOVE DOOR OF WHITE HOUSE\nFive Black and White Kittens Are Born Near President\u2019s\nExecutive Offices.\nIn a nest which she stole from a\nrobin, a pigeon today is sitting on eggs\nabove President Hoover\u2019s front door,\nthe main entrance to the White House,\nwhile a stray cat has presented the\nWhite House grounds with five tiny\nblack and white kittens, born not 100\nfeet from the front door of the Presi\ndent\u2019s executive offices.\nThe robin was a long time building\n1 Its nest safe on top of one of the\nornamental columns of the stately and\nfamous portico. The column top Juts\nout far enough from the west wall, to\nprovide a convenient nesting place, be\nneath the sheltering roof. Scarcely had\nthe robin finished the nest recently\nwhen a pigeon came along, drove the\nRAIL OFFICIALS CONFER\nWITH GRANT ON TRACKS\nPennsylvania Railroad officials con\nferred today with Lieut. Col. U. S.\nGrant, 3d, executive officer of the\nArlington Memorial Bridge Commis\nsion, on the question of relocating cer\ntain portions of the carrier\u2019s tracks\ngoing into Rosslyn, Va., so as to elimi\nnate grade crossings on extensions of\nproposed highways into Virginia.\nThe conference was made necessary\nby the rapidly approaching completion\nof the Arlington Memorial Bridge and\nby the Lee Boulevard project. It is\n-ft Thats what makes \u2019em so\nW\nJv/ififc the crispiest crackers you ever I\ni saw or tasted. I\nThat\u2019s the reason these dainty,\nslightly salted, flavorful squares\nare so delicious with soups, salads, sjp\"\nTHOUSAND WINDOW BAKERIES I\n..._' ~c\nrobin out, and today she was sitting\nserenly on her nest of eggs, while her\nproud consort preened himself on top\nof an adjacent column.\nThe five tiny kittens were presented\nto the White House grounds beneath\na snug, low-hanging evergreen bush\nnear the President\u2019s newly remodeled\nexecutive offices. Their eyes still are\nclosed kitten-like, to the bright light\nbeating down through the evergreens.\nEvidently alarmed by the big crowds\nfiling past the new home of her tiny\nkittens, the mother cat started today\nmoving them to another secluded spot\nsomewhere nearer the White House\nbuilding. A saucer of milk was provided\nfor the mother by men from the ex\necutive offices.\nproposed to run the tracks underneath\nthe highways, under tentative plans\nthat have been brought up.\nAttending the conference with the\nrailroad officials were MaJ. Douglas H.\nGillette, assistant to executive officer\nof the Arlington Memorial Bridge Com\nmission; Capt. E. N. Chisolm, Jr., engi\nneer .of the National Capital Park and\nPlanning Commission, and John Nagle,\narchitect In Col. Grant\u2019s office. Further\nthought will be given the subject and\npermanent plans drawn up at a later\ntime.\nThe Gold Coast of Africa is consider\ning a legislative proposal to form co\noperative societies among the agricul\nturists.\nSPEED BOND GRAFT\nCHARGES ARE AIRED\nComplaints Made in Hyatts\nville Are Sent to State\nOfficials.\nTransmisison to Gov. Albert C\nRitchie, State\u2019s Attorney J. Prank Par\nran of Prince Georges County, Col. E\nAustin Baughman, commissioner of mo\ntor vehicles, and the Prince Georgei\nCounty commissioners of testimony al\nleging the existence of a \u201cbonding racket\u2019 1\nin Prince Georges County as charged in\nHyattsville Police Court yesterday, con\nstituted the latest development today In\nthe American Automobile Association\u2019s\neffort to remedy a condition which has\ncaused numerous complaints.\nMeanwhile Sergt. John Joseph Cas\nsidy of the Maryland State police force,\nwho was assigned by Col. Baughman to\nInvestigate the complaints, searched the\ncourt records at Marlboro for cases of\npersons arrested and required to give\nbond for speeding in excess of 60 miles\nan hour, only to be tried for speeding\nmore than 40 miles an hour.\nThe testimony was presented before\nPolice Court Judge J. Chew Sheriff yes\nterday afternoon, but he refused to com\nment upon it, declaring it had revealed\nan Investigation on the part of Col.\nBaughman's office.\nOfficer Is Arrested.\nSergt. Cassidy, accompanied by an\nAmerican Automobile Association offi\ncial, was arrested by Deputy Sheriff\nRalph Brown early Monday morning\nand charged with speeding in excess of\n60 miles an hour. The sergeant was\nin civilian clothes and posed as an\nautomobile mechanic. It is alleged he\nwas required to pay SIOO for a SI,OOO\nbond and told a \u201chard luck story\u201d to\nthe bondsman, who is said to have\nagreed to attempt to have the speed\ning charges reduced, provided he would\nplead guilty.\nWhen Cassidy was arraigned yester\nday he was accused of speeding only\nIn excess of 40 miles an hour. To the\nsurprise of the parties Involved, he\npleaded not guilty.\nBrown told of pacing Cassidy at 57\nmiles an hour and when the court asked\nthe defendant if he cared to cross\nexamine the policeman Charles C. Col\nlins, attorney for the A. A. A., entered\nthe case as Cassidy\u2019s lawyer. Collins\nattempted to cross-examine Brown on\nhow the bond was obtained, but the\ncourt objected on the ground that it\nhad nothing to do with the speeding\ncharge. Collins replied that the fact\nthat SI,OOO bonds are required in 60-\nmile speeding cases was the only reason\nsuch charges were preferred.\nJudge Dismisses Case.\nHarry Heffner, a relative of Brown\u2019s,\nwho was with him when the arrest\nwas made, corroborated the deputy\u2019s\ntestimony. Cassidy was then called,\nand then it was revealed for the first\ntime that the supposed automobile\nmechanic was really a State policeman.\nAfter that there was no objection con\ncerning statements about the bond.\nHe and the A. A. A. official said\nthey were careful never to drive in ex\ncess of 85 miles an hour. G. D. Dun\nkum testified he tested Cassidy\u2019s speed\nometer and found it 4 miles fast at 55\nmiles per hour. Judge Sheriff ruled\nhe was speeding in line of duty and dis\nmissed the case.\nCassidy declared that in four years\non the police force he could not recall\never making an arrest for 60 miles\u2019\nspeed. Very few motorists go over\n50, he said.\nBrown consistently denied having\nbeen approached by the bondsman to\nreduce the speed charge, and insisted\nhe amended the warrant of his own\nvolition because Cassidy appealed to\nhim, and he wanted to \u201chelp the\n'mechanic' out.\u201d\nEvidence was introduced to show that\nGeorge D. Strayer, Jr., and Francis C.\nHough had been arrested in recent\nweeks, had similar experiences to that\nof Cassidy, and complained to the\nA. A. A.\nCassidy has been stationed in West\nern Maryland, where he gained con\nsiderable publicity last Summer by ar\nresting Chairman C. G. Uhle of the\nState Roads Commission on a traffic\ncharge. Brown has figured in several\ncases that have attracted wide atten\ntion. Only two weeks ago he arrested\nI a Mount Rainier town bailiff on an\nintoxication charge, which so aroused\nthe town\u2019s officials they held a special\ncouncil meeting, exonerated the bailiff\nand asked for disciplinary action against\nBrown by the county commissioners.\nFainter Prefers Blondes.\nNEW YORK, May 1 (/P). \u2014A golden\nblonde with perfect color scheme is the\nchoice of Leo Quanchi, portrait painter,\nfor the most beautiful woman in Amer\nica. He is to show his portrait of Dor\nothy Hall, actress, at a Paris exhibition.\nHe describes her hair as of spun gold,\neyes sky blue, cheeks pink, lips a rich\nred and teeth dazzling.\n\nChild Is Poisoned\nBy Eating Lye, Put\nOut to Kill Rats\nLeonard Yates, 16 months old,\nof 415 East Capitol street, is in\na serious condition today at Chil\ndren\u2019s Hospital, where he is\nsuffering from poisoning. The\nyoungster crawled to a corner\nwhere lye had been placed to kill\nrats and ate it.\nHis mother rushed the child to\nCasualty Hospital, where he was\ntreated by Dr. Louis Jimal. Later,\nhe was removed to Children's\nHospital for special treatment.\nIt is believed he will recover.\nTWO STILL IN JAIL\nIN HIT-AND-RUN CASE\nWomen Accused in Death of\nCyclist Are Unable to Furnish\n$5,000 Bond.\nUnable to furnish bond of $5,000 each,\nMiss Martha Louise Russell, 24 years\nold, of 204 D street northeast, and Mrs.\nLillian E. Walsh, 20 years old, of 1223\nFifteenth street, held for the District of\nColumbia grand jury yesterday by a\ncoroner\u2019s jury as alleged operators of\na hit-and-run machine which crushed\nand hurled to death Fillmore Ray, 21-\nyear-old colored bicyclist, on Canal road\nMonday night, were still lodged in the\nDistrict Jail this morning.\nPolicemen testified that Mrs. Walsh\nInformed them Miss Russell was driving\nand became panicky after the accident,\ninsisting on driving away from the scene\nbecause she did not have a permit and\nwas afraid of being arrested.\nNeither woman made any statement\nduring the hearing.\nCHILD SEVERELY BURNED\nBY DISINFECTING FLUID\nFulls Bottle From Dresser as Fam\nily Prepares to Move,\nParents Report.\nDale Butler, 18 months old. son of\nMr. and Mrs. A. O. Butler, 1452 Euclid\nstreet, is in a serious condition at\nEmergency Hospital today as a result\nof burns sustained on his face, throat\nand chest, when he spilled a bottle of\ndisinfectant on himself last night\nThe parents reported that Dale and\nhis brother Don, 3 years old, were play\ning in the bed room of their home.\nVarious belongings were scattered about\nthe room as the Butler family was\npreparing to move, and among them\nthe \u201cdisinfectant\u201d on a dresser. Dale\npulled at the linen cover to the dresser\nfrom below, and down came the bottle!\nMrs. Butler, in another room, at\ntracted by the screams of her son,\nrushed to the room, picked up the\nsmall boy and carried him across\nEuclid street to a neighborhood doctor.\nHe was later transferred to Emergency\nDon, through halting speech, related\nto his father the events leading to the\naccident. At the hospital It is reported\nthat Dale had a chance for recovery,!\nalthough it is feared that the acid\nmight have severely injured his eyes.\nG. H. CALVERT, Jr., NAMED\nMARYLAND SOCIETY HEAD\nOther Officers Are Elected at An\nnual Meeting Held at Wash\nington Club.\nElection of officers of the Maryland\nState Society of Washington took place\nat the annual meeting of the society\nlast night at the Washington Club.\nGeorge H. Calvert, Jr., was elected pres\nident for the ensuing year.\nThe following other officers were\nelected: John Ritchie, Jr., first viae\npresident; John Marshall Boteler, sec\nond vice president; Miss Mary W. Mer\nrick, third vice president; Miss Emma\niM. Leker, corresponding secretary;\nMiss Virginia Hebb, recording secretary;\nClement W. Sheriff, treasurer, and Ral\neigh Sherman, historian.\nII\nt;>: v;i''-\u2018''\u2019\u2022>%)'4\nv t s\n>4V l| t\u2018*V N *&V\\\nf >kIH^H^HI\n\u25a0Pf |Nm Just one of\nfrom ailments of this nature* aggravated by harsh toilet tissue\nHabits of personal cleanliness processed to satisfy the three re*\nhave very little to do with the quirements doctors say toilet ti\u00bb*\norigin of rectal trouble. sue must have to be safe. absorb*\nllffll! For even the most immaculate ency\u2014softness\u2014chemical purity.\n3 for Ir\u00abIn li J\u00bb f 3 run the risk of serious illness every Each sheet is made up of million*\n9C\u00a3 MMSKm/M time a harsh or chemically im- of \"thirsty fibres\nP ure toilet tissue is used. These specially treated fibres,\nIfeU, A~- T Yet despite this serious danger, soft and clothlike, are extremely\nii|4\u00abjiWMy in thousands of homes you will absorbent Without this absorb*\nfind toilet tissues utterly unfit for ent quality, thorough hygiene is\nc ome are a2e 4 sharp-edged Scott Tissues are made from\nWRkIIS Some are covered with nny shy fresh, clean materials No harmful\nIwwl MS me a *j e ven cfiwnicallv dy es No waste material They\naWnffSi S^matSfd 6 fr m rec aimed are sanitary Fully sterilized-and\n\u25a0jftjLgfiUyiMMjl absolutely safe to use It doesn't\nScot Tissue, Sam-Tissue pay to be careless in this bathroom\nant |_ Waldorf are famous essential Always insist on Scot*\nbatbroom tissucs specially Tissue\u2014Sani-Tissue or Waldorf,\n\u00bb*w fwgs# Scoitlissues\nbuilt-in fixtures m-NmHIH Scot Tissue and Waldorf are the two largest selling\nbrands in the world. Sani-Tissue is the new popular priced\nl> white toilet tissue embodying the famous ibirstyfikn qualities*\n.;\u00bb\u00abfUfew*\u00bb\u25a0\u25a0 -*i to*\nBRADY BOMB CASE\nGOES TO ROCKVILLE\nDefense Attorney Cannot\nSee Fair Trial at Up\nper Marlboro.\nBy a Staff Correspondent of The Star.\nUPPER MARLBORO, Md., May I.\nThe long-expected request for removal\nfrom Prince Georges County of the\ntrial of Lawrence Leroy Brady and his\nbrother, Herman Brady, who were In\ndicted for the Seat Pleasant bomb mur\nders, was filed by defense counsel yes\nterday and resulted In Circuit Court\nJudge Joseph C. Mattingly ordering the\ncase sent to Rockville.\nIn an affidavit to the court Defense\nAttorneys M. Hampton Magruder, Lans\ndale G. Sasscer and Frank Hall declared\ntheir clients \u201cmay not get a fair trial\nunless the records of the case are sent\nto another county.\u201d\nDate for the trial of the Bradys Is\nexpected to be set Monday when the\nthree judges of the circuit assemble in\nRockville to hear arguments in the libel\nsuit against the Rockville Independent\neditor and others.\nAlthough defense attorneys have been\nnon-committal since the Bradys were\nindicted as to whether or not they\nwould ask for a removal, it was gener\nally expected at the county seat that\nthey would seek a change of venue. The\ncase has been so widely discussed\nthroughout Prince Georges County that\ncourt house officials anticipated diffi\nculty even in obtaining a jury.\nThe Bradys were indicted two weeks\nago following a protracted investigation\nby the grand jury. The presentments\nreturned by that body accused the\nbrothers jointly of the murders result\ning when a bomb, disguised as a Christ\nmas present, exploded in the home of\nJohn Hall, in Seat Pleasant, on New\nYear day.\nMrs. Naomi Hall Brady, wife of Her\nman, to whom the package containing\nthe bomb was addressed, was instantly\nkilled. Her baby brother, Samuel, and\nher sister, Dorothy, died a few days\nlater from wounds inflicted by the ex\nplosion.\nLocusts Swarm in Rumania.\nBUCHAREST, May 1 (&).\u2014An im\nmense swarm of locusts descended upon\nRumania yesterday, attacking 20,000\nacres of vineyards in the district of\nKujudshuk, in the Dobruja region.\nYoung plants were destroyed.\nThe fertile plains of the Danube are\nalso threatened.\nv Greatest money's worth! y\n5-crop Boscul Coffee\nExquisite flavor possible only through 99\nyears* recognized coffee leadership.\nBlended from the world\u2019s best\ncoffees. Aged in the bean.\nVacuum >packed.\nOven-fresh\nin your H|\nenp.\nQHt Ktsius-sst***'\nS|corr\u00a3a\nfa. 8\u00abo!i\nc\nWHY DEWY YOURSELF THE BEST COFFKIT\nVISITOR INJURED\nIN AUTO MISHAP\nDriver of Car Which Hit Park\ned Machine Held on Per\nmit Charge.\nMiss May Walsh, 61, of New Haven,\nConn., is confined to the Emergency\nHospital with a serious fracture of\nthe right hip suffered late yesterday\nwhen an automobile driven by Frank\nH. Butler, 21, colored, of 79 Florida\navenue, crashed into a parked machine\nbeside which she was standing at Fif\nteenth near L street.\nMiss Walsh, who 1s stopping at the\nHighlands Apartments, California street\nand Connecticut avenue, was hurled to\nthe street by the impact. She was re\nmoved to the hospital in a passing au\ntomobile and treated by Dr. John E.\nLewis. Hospital officials reported to\nday that her condition is undetermined.\nPvt. E. P. Hartman of No. 3 police\nstation took Butler into custody and\nbooked him on a charge of operating\nan automobile without a driver\u2019s permit.\nMiss Evelyn Jett, 21-year-old tele\nphone operator, of 1026 Fourth street\nnortheast, suffered a wrenched shoul\nder and back and minor contusions of\nthe knees late yesterday when an auto\nmobile in which she was an occupant\nwas in a collision at Fourteenth and\nR streets with a car operated by Paul\nD. Haines of 1219 I street.\nJUST ARRIVED!\nFresh Shipment of\nMountain Valley\nMineral Water\nfrom Hot Springs,\nArkansas.\nWE DELIVER\nMountain Valley Water\nCo.\n21S District National Bank Bldg.\n1406 G St. N.W.\nMETROPOLITAN IM2","height":"25488","width":"19881"}}
